[1] Argentina
Date: Thu 2 Apr 2009
Source: Inter Press Service (IPS) [edited]
<http://www.ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=46371>


Argentina is suffering its worst epidemic of dengue fever since 1998
in terms of the number of people and the size of the area affected.
And on top of that, the most dangerous form of the illness [DHF],
never recorded [there] before, has made its appearance.

"There is a major outbreak of the disease and it is more serious than
in other years, because the number of infected people is larger and
more provinces are involved," Dr Alfredo Seijo, a specialist in
infectious diseases in charge of the Dengue Unit at the Muniz
Hospital in Buenos Aires, told IPS.

But official information about the epidemic is confusing. The figures
mentioned so far by the national authorities are much lower than
those communicated by local officials and other healthcare personnel.

Argentina's Health Minister, Graciela Ocana, admitted this week that
the situation "is serious" and sent extra help to the northern
province of Chaco, the most affected area, in spite of the provincial
government's reluctance to acknowledge the problem.

Ocana said Monday [30 Mar 2009] that 4147 people had contracted the
dengue virus in 6 provinces, and that most of them had been infected
on Argentine soil. Only about 400 are "imported" cases, that is,
people who have acquired the virus in another country or region.
However, a confidential report by the Chaco provincial emergency
committee for dengue prevention and control stated that there were
already 11 363 confirmed cases. In Charata alone, a town of 35 000
people in southwestern Chaco, the local authorities have recorded
more than 4000 dengue sufferers.

In Argentina even the most conservative figures, such as those
reported by the Health Ministry, lead to the conclusion that the
epidemic is the worst since the virus reappeared in the country in
the late 1990s. In the intervening period, the worst outbreaks
occurred in 2004 and 2007, with nearly 2000 cases reported on each
occasion, according to the ministry's Epidemiology Department.

So far the Health Ministry has not reported any fatal cases, but in
Chaco, 2 women are said to have died from the illness, and another
death has been reported in the adjacent province of Salta.

The Health Ministry in Salta reported 8 cases of DHF in March, but
the national ministry only recognises 3 cases in Chaco, and none in
Salta.

Rolando Nunez, of the non-governmental Nelson Mandela Research and
Study Centre based in Resistencia, the provincial capital, told IPS
that Chaco province combines several of the factors that can fuel the
spread of dengue fever. "Nearly 70 percent of the population lacks
piped water," the activist said. And at times of drought, the
situation is even worse. Last July [2008] the Provincial Water
Administration announced that it was building reservoirs to collect
rainwater in the wet season. Meanwhile, the health authorities are
encouraging people to get rid of the pots and containers they use to
collect rainwater for their own consumption, in order to eliminate
mosquitoes.

[Byline: Marcela Valente]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Susan Baekeland

[The 3 Apr 2009 edition of Clarin (in Spanish)
(<http://www.clarin.com/diario/2009/04/03/sociedad/s-01890196.htm>)
reported that the provinces with locally acquired dengue cases are
Salta, Jujuy, Formosa, and with recent expansion into Tucuman,
Catamarca, Chaco, and Corrientes provinces. There have been 4 deaths
and one case is under study. Imported cases are reported in the
provinces Neuquen, La Pampa, Buenos Aires, Mendoza, La Rioja,
Catamarca, Cordoba, Enter Rios, Santa Fe, and Formosa and in the city
of Buenos Aires.

A map of Argentina showing the provinces mentioned can be accessed at
