[2] Bolivia
Date: Mon 30 Mar 2009
Source: Terra, Reuters report [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY]
<http://www.terra.com.mx/articulo.aspx?articuloId=806744&ref=1>


The dengue cases in Bolivia have declined in the most recent weeks
and health authorities estimated on Monday [30 Mar 2009] that within
a month the worst epidemic of this disease in the country in 20 years
will end. It has taken the lives of 22 people since December [2008].
The epidemic, which at its peak exceeded 1500 cases daily, has begun
to be controlled and in the past week declined to 200 new cases
reported each day, said authorities. "We are very satisfied because
we are improving the dengue containment levels. We have had good
news; however we must not lower our guard," said the minister of
health, Ramiro Tapia in the eastern city of Santa Cruz, where more
than 75 percent of the cases were reported.

To date, the number of classical dengue cases totaled more than 53
000 and 127 DHF [cases].

[Byline: Diego Ore]

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is gratifying to see the sharp decline in the number of dengue
cases, which have been so great recently as to overwhelm medical
facilities and providers, especially in the city of Santa Cruz. It
would be of interest to know the economic impact of dengue in this
area, which is an economic engine of Bolivia, in terms of both lost
workdays and in direct and indirect medical costs. Of course, it is
not possible to accurately calculate the value of lives lost in human
terms.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Bolivia can be accessed at
