[5] Viet Nam (Ho Chi Minh City)
Date: Tue 31 Mar 2009
Source: Viet Nam News [edited]
<http://vietnamnews.vnagency.com.vn/showarticle.php?num=01HEA310309>


Cases of dengue continue to rise
--------------------------------
The number of dengue fever cases in HCM [Ho Chi Minh] City in the 1st
quarter of this year [2009] has increased by 8 percent compared with
the same period a year ago [2008], according to the municipal
Department of Health. To date, the department has recorded 2250
people hospitalised with dengue fever, one of whom died.

Many hospitals in the city have reported increasing numbers of dengue
fever cases over the last several months. Dr Tran Van Ngoc, head of
the HCM City Tropical Disease Hospital's Paediatrics A Ward, says the
ward has been receiving an average of 10 dengue fever patients per
day.

Dr Vu Quang Vinh, deputy head of Paediatrics Hospital No 2's general
accounting department, says that the hospital has received 124 cases
so far this month [March 2009].

The situation is rather serious, says Dr Nguyen Dac Tho, deputy
director of the city's Preventative Health Centre. He says a survey
conducted by the centre in districts 12, 6, and Binh Thanh found
disease-carrying mosquitoes in more than 90 percent of the houses.

To discuss ways to prevent new outbreaks in the upcoming rainy season
in southern provinces, the Ministry of Health's Preventive Medicine
Department held a meeting on Friday [27 Mar 2009] with
representatives of provincial health departments on implementing the
National Dengue Fever Prevention Programme.

A representative from the Preventive Medicine Department said this
year [2009], the ministry would run the National Dengue Fever
Prevention Programme in all provinces and cities nationwide at a cost
of more than VND 91 billion (USD 5.2 million).

The programme aims to reduce, by the end of this year [2009], both
the number of people infected and those dying from dengue fever by 10
percent over the average during the 2003-07 period.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-MBDS
<promed-mbds@promedmail.org>

[Control of mosquito vectors would be the most important measure in
order to reduce the morbidity and mortality of dengue infection as
mosquitoes were found in more than 90 percent of the houses during a
survey in Ho Chi Minh City. As the monsoon season is approaching, the
mosquitoes and their breeding places should be eliminated to prevent
dengue outbreak in the incoming rainy season. As of 10 Feb 2009,
there had been more than 3000 cases of dengue fever reported
nationwide in Viet Nam during 2009 (see prior PRO/MBDS posting Dengue
- Viet Nam 20090211.0614).

For maps of Viet Nam with provinces, see
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/vietnam_admin01.jpg> and
<http://www.angelfire.com/co/hongnam/vnmap.html>.

